    <p>

        Co-occurring disorders, also known as dual diagnoses or dual disorders, are the presence of a substance use
        disorder as well as a mental health disorder in the same person. Substance use disorders can range from mild
        abuse to severe dependence, and are characterized by an inability to control or abstain from substance use, as
        well as physical dependence in some cases.

        <br><br>

        Mood and anxiety disorders, as well as severe mental illnesses such as schizophrenia and schizoaffective
        disorder, are some of the most common mental health disorders found in people with substance use disorders.
        People who have substance use disorders are also more likely to develop other primary conditions or chronic
        diseases, as well as to have mental health problems.

    </p>

